Registration is now open for TCOE’s second annual Equity Conference entitled Equity for All: Inclusion Starts with “I.” The virtual conference – planned for January 21 from 8:00 a.m. until 3:00 p.m. – will feature two prominent keynote speakers, Dr. Jamila Lyiscott and Father Greg Boyle. Additionally, the interactive institute will include a wide variety of breakout sessions engaging participants in deeper conversations around equity challenges impeding student success and brainstorming practical solutions that empower all members of the educational community. Participants will complete the conference equipped with new tools to use in equity strategies at their own schools.

Educators, community members, and parents are encouraged to visit tcoe.org/EquityConference for registration information. The fee for Tulare County residents is $15 per person; attendees outside Tulare County may attend for $25 per person.

Can you find good character through distance learning? Does it exist in the virtual world? Absolutely!

The Tulare County Office of Education is delighted to accept nominations for the 25th Annual Kids of Character Awards beginning today! What started as a celebration of students modeling the Six Pillars of Character in 1996, has turned into a national character recognition model which has honored tens of thousands of Tulare County students!

Educators, parents, and community members are encouraged to take a few moments to nominate Tulare County students (grades TK-12) who are exhibiting great character during these challenging times. Do you see great character online or around the house? Are your students doing something extraordinary to help the community? Nominate them today!

The nomination period is open through September 24. Nominated Tulare County students will be recognized during National CHARACTER COUNTS! Week, October 19-24.

Visit www.tcoe.org/KidsOfCharacter today.

Sorry Pluto. On this day 14 years ago, to everyone's disappointment, Pluto was demoted to dwarf planet status. To be a planet, an object must meet three criteria: 1) it must orbit the Sun... check; 2) it must be big enough that its gravity gives it a sphere shape... check; and 3) it can't cross the orbit of another planet. Unfortunately, it hasn't done that. Bye-bye, Pluto!

Follow us to receive regular astronomy updates from TCOE's Planetarium & Science Center.

Equity leader Dr. Paul Gorski is returning to Tulare County this fall to conduct a six-part, virtual training series beginning October 7 for educators in Tulare and surrounding counties. Through this series, Dr. Gorski will expand on his presentation delivered at the first annual TCOE Equity Conference in January 2020. He will share a set of equity principles and the knowledge base and skills to guide any equity practice toward its central goal: to identify and eliminate inequity within our school communities.

Participants should plan to commit to the entire series. Visit tulare.k12oms.org/147-189605 to register today!

Forty-three years ago, Voyager 2 was launched on a mission, sending it to the edge of our solar system and beyond. It’s still hurtling through interstellar space at nearly 35,000 miles per hour, more than 11 billion miles away. That's about three times the distance from the Sun to the edge of the solar system. Stay tuned next week for an activity to build your own scale model of the solar system!

Follow us to receive regular astronomy updates from TCOE's Planetarium & Science Center.

Last fall, all University Preparatory High School (UPHS) civics students submitted their Civic Action Projects to a contest sponsored by the Constitutional Rights Foundation (CRF). Last year was the first year civics teacher Arturo Figueroa had his students submit their projects to the organization's contest. Through the contest, CRF provides an opportunity for seniors throughout the country to improve their communities through civic action.

Yesterday, Mr. Figueroa learned that the project developed by three UPHS students (Aubrey, Britney, and Corina) took first place in the 2020 CRF Civic Action Project contest! Their project focused on UPHS student safety on the College of the Sequoias Visalia campus.

UPHS faculty and staff are extremely proud of these three young women, who are now UPHS alumni! Congratulations to Arturo Figueroa for your leadership, and Aubrey, Britney, and Corina for your outstanding work!

View their project at https://crfcap.org/mod/page/view.php?id=208#filter-tabs-content-1-2.

Next week, the Mathematics Department is offering Zoom trainings to equip teachers in today's virtual learning environments!

Teachers of students in grades 3-8 are invited to learn how growth mindset can be utilized in a distance learning environment to improve math education for all. Based on brain research, growth mindset supports both social-emotional and academic development. This training is offered August 25.

Teachers of students in grades K-6 and 6-12 are invited to a Math Boot Camp on adapting math instruction to distance learning. Participants will learn the tools available them to facilitate learning, engage students in peer-to-peer interactions, and assess their progress! These trainings are offered August 24 or August 26.

Register today by visiting tulare.k12oms.org

Where has the Moon gone? It's there; it's just gone dark. This moon phase is called New Moon. During this phase, the Moon passes between the Earth and the sun, which means the illuminated side of the Moon is pointed away from Earth. This is the beginning of the Moon's cycle and a great time to observe the constellations using our downloadable Astronomy Wheel at bit.ly/3gz0EQK.

Follow us to receive regular astronomy updates from TCOE's Planetarium & Science Center.

Videos of the 41 Zoom sessions in TCOE's Virtual Learning Conference (held August 4) are now available on our Distance Learning website. To view them, visit tcoe.org/DistanceLearning and click on the "Virtual Learning Conference" banner.

TCOE held its first Virtual Learning Conference for educators and parents on August 4, attracting over 1,600 registrants.

Parents attended a variety of sessions, including two conducted in Spanish. Topics included support with virtual tools and platforms, IEPs, preparing for college and career, and engaging their children in learning at home.

Educators and parents of children with special needs attended sessions on building effective communication within the IEP team, social/emotional learning, resource mapping and matching for student needs, and mindfulness. The special education strand also featured a teacher panel.

Topics for educators also included content-area presentations on English language arts, history/social science, math, art, science, and technology, with several sessions on supporting English learners through virtual instruction.

Aided by distance learning and technology trainings obtained this summer, University Preparatory High School (UPHS) teachers have been back in their classrooms supporting students learning at home for nearly two weeks! Language arts, math, science, history, music, drama, and physical education are all being delivered virtually with excitement that they report makes them feel like "first year teachers all over again!" Not only are they delivering instruction in all subject areas, but providing additional emotional and mindfulness supports.

Thank you UPHS teachers for your tremendous efforts to make the 2020-21 school year a great one, despite the challenges of distance learning!

TCOE welcomes Sarah Maokosy, D.M., K12 Pathway Coordinator with the College and Career program. Dr. Maokosy will be serving many of the districts in the Tulare Kings College Career Collaborative and the College of the Sequoias to align Career Technical Education (CTE) pathways with higher education programs.

Dr. Maokosy recently served as adjunct faculty for business at Reedley College, West Hills College Lemoore, and Fresno State, and as CEO Club advisor and Entrepreneurship Center assistant coordinator at Reedley College. This year, she also completed her Doctorate in Organizational Leadership degree. Dr. Maokosy is a decorated Army veteran who still makes it her goal to help other female veterans transition successfully to civilian life and the workforce.

Welcome Dr. Maokosy!

Tonight's stellar forecast – a third quarter moon with a chance of meteor showers. Tonight, the Perseid meteor shower will be at its peak in the northeastern, predawn sky near the constellation Perseus. This meteor shower is caused by Earth currently passing through the debris trail of Comet Swift-Tuttle. Download our free, handy Astronomy Wheel to help you find constellation Perseus (bit.ly/3gz0EQK)!

Follow us to receive regular astronomy updates from TCOE's Planetarium & Science Center.

NASA is heading back to Mars! The rover Perseverance launched today on its mission to explore the red planet, this time with a little extra "Ingenuity" in the form of a helicopter. The Ingenuity helicopter will mark the first time powered flight is attempted on another planet. There are only a few flights planned for this experimental aircraft, but if successful it will mark a huge leap forward in how we explore the red planet. Perseverance and Ingenuity are expected to land on Mars in February 2021.

Want to learn more about Ingenuity and even make your own helicopter? Download our free activity: https://bit.ly/33hZ6qK.

Follow us to receive regular astronomy updates from TCOE's Planetarium & Science Center.

This week, three Tulare County district employees received notification that they were the winners in the 2020 Excellence in Education Awards program. The winners are Administrator/Manager of the Year Philip Pierschbacher of the Tulare City School District, Teacher of the Year Stacy Trapletti of Cherry Avenue Middle School in Tulare, and School Employee of the Year Micaela Macareno of the Cutler-Orosi Joint Unified School District.

“The common trait we see in these fine individuals is that they have taken on responsibilities far beyond their regular duties,” said Tim Hire, Tulare County Superintendent of Schools. “They have used their talents to advance their schools and their districts, creating extraordinary educational cultures and practices for the benefit of their students.”

Read about the winners at tcoe.org/NewsGallery. Thank you Educational Employees Credit Union | EECU for being our partner in recognizing extraordinary educators and school employees for 26 years!

Tulare City School District, Cutler-Orosi Joint Unified School District

Comet NEOWISE is paying Earth a visit. The comet should be visible over the next few weeks, but when it's gone, it won't return for 6,800 years! To spot it, look to the northwest horizon around 9:45 pm, just below the Big Dipper.

Need some help finding it? Look for the constellation Ursa Major using our handy Astronomy Wheel. You’ll find the Big Dipper is part of that larger constellation (astronomers call that an “asterism”). Our Astronomy Wheel can be downloaded at: bit.ly/3gz0EQK.

Follow us to receive regular astronomy updates from TCOE's Planetarium & Science Center.

It's a good night to dust off that telescope! You can catch Jupiter at its brightest tonight in the southern sky as the gas giant reaches “opposition." Opposition occurs when a superior planet (Mars, Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, Neptune) and the Sun are on opposite sides of the Earth, forming a strait line. Jupiter can be spotted with the naked eye in the southern sky all night in the constellation Sagittarius.

Need help finding it? Download our free, handy Astronomy Wheel to help navigate the night sky at bit.ly/3gz0EQK. For an added bonus, use a telescope to see Jupiter's banding, great red spot, and its four Galilean moons.

Follow us to receive regular astronomy updates from TCOE's Planetarium & Science Center.

Let's celebrate the stars and explore the night sky! Today is Tanabata, the Japanese star festival which pays tribute to the legend of Orihime (represented by the star Vega) and Hikoboshi (represented by the star Altair). Theirs is a story of star-crossed lovers separated by a celestial river (represented by the Milky Way). According to legend, for one day on the seventh day of the seventh month, the two are united by a bridge made of magpies.

Find Altair and Vega and their constellations Aquila and Lyra in the night sky using our handy Astronomy Wheel!

Download it here: https://psc-cdn.s3-us-west-1.amazonaws.com/TCOE_PSC-Astronomy-Wheel-v4.pdf

Follow us to receive regular astronomy updates from TCOE's Planetarium & Science Center.

The Special Services Division has two new managers to oversee AcCEL Programs in the Porterville and Visalia areas. TCOE veteran teacher Katrina Smith will manage Porterville-area programs while Brian Cordero will oversee programs in the Visalia area.

Katrina Smith has been in the field of special education for over 10 years. She began her career as a Resource Specialist Program (RSP) teacher before teaching within the TCOE AcCEL Program. She is the new program manager for AcCEL in the Porterville area, which includes the L.B. Hill Learning Center and 15 special day classes and community based instruction programs.

Brian Cordero is the new program manager for AcCEL in the Visalia area, which includes the Occupational Training Program Learning Center and 15 special day classes and community based instruction programs. Brian comes to Tulare County from the Bay Area where he was a lead teacher for Project SEARCH, a vocational internship program for young adults with significant disabilities.

Congratulations Katrina and Brian!

The Theatre Company is proud to release two versions of the virtual children’s musical, THE SHOW MUST GO ONLINE! The Theatre Company created the production this summer utilizing two casts – students who were scheduled to perform in the Theatre Company’s Spring Musical Revue, which was cancelled in April.

THE SHOW MUST GO ONLINE! is the story of students in a school musical who decide that their show shouldn’t be cancelled by restrictions developed during the COVID-19 pandemic. They decide instead to produce the show's individual scenes in their own homes and share them online.

Enjoy the half-hour production with two casts at www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLEZVjC88Ozr6K_l_HaQFLXx6Vi2bzIU-F

Happy 290th birthday, Charles Messier! Messier was a French astronomer best known for surveying and cataloging 110 space objects including galaxies, star clusters, and nebula. Since most of these objects are relatively bright, many amateur astronomers use his catalog like a cosmic checklist of things to find in the night sky.

Want to explore Messier's catalog yourself? Download our Messier Object Bingo kit. Just follow the link, print and cut the cards, and then have a designated caller pick a random object card from the deck. The first player to have four objects in a pattern wins!

The Messier bingo kit can be downloaded from this link: https://psc-cdn.s3-us-west-1.amazonaws.com/Messier_Bingo_0006.pdf

Follow us to receive regular astronomy updates from TCOE's Planetarium & Science Center.

Not only is Father's Day coming up on Sunday, it's also a busy weekend for cosmic events. Summer officially starts Saturday with the summer solstice, the day of the year with the most daylight. This happens for us when the Earth's northern hemisphere is at its maximum tilt toward the sun. The Moon also begins its cycle with a New Moon on Sunday, putting it in a perfect position for a rare "Ring of Fire" solar eclipse. Unfortunately we won't be able to see it in our region, but you can watch online Sunday at 9:00 p.m. at this link: https://www.timeanddate.com/live/eclipse-solar-2020-june-21.

Follow us to receive regular astronomy updates from TCOE's Planetarium & Science Center.

Follow us to receive regular astronomy updates from TCOE's Planetarium & Science Center.

May is Mental Health Awareness Month. In these uncertain times, setting up a bedtime routine which promotes quality sleep is very important to our overall mental health! When we are tired, it’s harder to regulate our emotions and cope with challenging situations. This is especially true for children who may already struggle to express their feelings. Creating a bedtime routine which promotes relaxation may include a mindfulness practice, a warm bath, a bedtime story and cuddles, and/or sipping a warm beverage. It is also important to end screen time at least 1-2 hours before bed.

For more resources from TCOE's Behavioral Health Services, visit https://www.tulareselpa.org/copy-of-aap

Child Care providers,
TCOE Resource & Referral has received one-time funding from the California Department of Education to support Cleaning and Supplies for Child Care Providers (CSCP). Providers must be currently open or intend to reopen during the COVID-19 emergency to be eligible for these funds.

Providers of all types are encouraged to participate. This includes all licensed child care centers, Family Child Care Homes (FCCH), and family, friend or neighbor (license-exempt) care providers who provide care to children in our county.

If you are interested in applying for these funds, please complete the Self-Certification Form and W-9 Form at these links:

Self Certification Form -https://www.cde.ca.gov/sp/cd/re/documents/providerselfcertifyform.pdf

W-9 Form (English) - https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-pdf/fw9.pdf

Please email these completed forms to cscp@tcoe.org by May 15. Funding will be distributed on a first-come, first-served basis until exhausted. Thank you for providing essential services to the families and children in Tulare County!

Spot the Moon this afternoon entering its next phase, "First Quarter." You'll notice it's a half moon, not a quarter, right?

Follow us to receive regular astronomy updates from TCOE's Planetarium & Science Center.

Tune in on Sunday, May 3, at 6:30 p.m. to see ABC30's latest Children First special "Coping During COVID-19." The special will feature a number of inspiring stories and interviews with Tulare County educators and students.

Among them is an interview with TCOE’s Dr. Jennifer Newell, director of Behavioral Health Services, who offers parents tips on how to support their children during difficult times and shares apps that can help reduce anxiety. Katherine Goyette, educational technology specialist with Educational Resource Services, was also interviewed to share how teachers are using digital resources to connect with students via distance learning.

The highlight of the program will be a forum hosted by Margot. Kim featuring six students from six valley schools. Among them are three Tulare County seniors representing Granite Hills High School in Porterville, Tulare Western High School, and Redwood High School in Visalia. The students will share how the pandemic has impacted their lives and how they are coping.
text:
Tune in on Sunday, May 3, at 6:30 p.m. to see ABC30's latest Children First special "Coping During COVID-19." The special will feature a number of inspiring stories and interviews with Tulare County educators and students.

Among them is an interview with TCOE’s Dr. Jennifer Newell, director of Behavioral Health Services, who offers parents tips on how to support their children during difficult times and shares apps that can help reduce anxiety. Katherine Goyette, educational technology specialist with Educational Resource Services, was also interviewed to share how teachers are using digital resources to connect with students via distance learning.

The highlight of the program will be a forum hosted by Margot. Kim featuring six students from six valley schools. Among them are three Tulare County seniors representing Granite Hills High School in Porterville, Tulare Western High School, and Redwood High School in Visalia. The students will share how the pandemic has impacted their lives and how they are coping.

Want to spot a planet in the night sky? It's easy tonight! Just look west at dusk and you'll find Venus shining at its maximum brightness for the year. You can see it through a telescope, binoculars, or even with a sharp eye. After this week, Venus will slowly start to dim before it disappears in the sun's glare at the end of May, reappearing in early June.

Fun fact: Venus spins around the sun on its axis upside down!

Follow us to receive regular astronomy updates from TCOE's Planetarium & Science Center.

post_text: The TCOE Planetarium & Science Center is forecasting meteors tonight! Later this evening through early tomorrow morning is a great time to view the annual Lyrid meteor shower. Meteors will be visible in the northeast sky from about 10:00 p.m. until dawn, peaking at around 2:00 a.m. when 10 to 15 meteors per hour will be visible. This meteor shower is the result of Earth crossing the orbital path of Comet Thatcher, which last visited the inner solar system in 1861!

In response to the growing COVID-19 pandemic, Tulare County Superintendent of Schools Tim Hire announced that the Tulare County Office of Education, its schools, and Early Childhood Education Child Development Centers will remain closed until further notice. This includes La Sierra Charter School, University Preparatory High School, and all Court/Community Schools. This announcement supersedes a previous directive to close TCOE programs until April 2, with schools and Child Development Centers to be closed until April 14.

During this closure, TCOE staff will be working from home Monday through Friday from 8:00 a.m. until 5:00 p.m. You may reach them by email. Essential services that require staff to work at their normal location will be continued at specific times during the closure.

Don't gather; stay safe at home.

TCOE’s California Center on Teaching Careers, in partnership with CSU Bakersfield and Visalia Unified School District, is seeking 30 aspiring educators for its Teacher Residency for Rural Education (TRRE) project. Through the 18-month graduate program, participants will earn a single subject credential with a focus in STEM (Science, Technology, Engineering, Mathematics), a master’s degree in education with an emphasis in curriculum and instruction, and receive a stipend for living expenses.

Those interested in applying to the TRRE Program, which will begin its first cohort in the fall of 2020, are encouraged visit www.thecenter-trreproject.org/sign-up to submit an inquiry form for details about an online informational meeting.

The TRRE project is primarily funded through the Teacher Quality Partnership Grant Program; however, the National Center on Teacher Residency, the Bank Street School, Visalia Unified School District, Stanford Teacher Education Program, and a cadre of community-based partners have also contributed toward this program.

TheCenter-TRREProject.org

Congratulations Adeline Boling, Tulare County's 2020 Spelling Champion! The fifth grader from Conyer Elementary in Visalia went 23 rounds to win with the word “kerplunk.”

This year, the competition attracted a total of 223 spellers in grades 4-8 from public and private Tulare County schools.

The second place winner was Kirsten Solmantil, an eighth-grade student at St. Anne’s School in Porterville. Dylan Ridgway, an eighth grader from Green Acres Middle School, Visalia; and Kalea Mariboho, an eighth grader from Springville Union School, tied for third.

Adeline will represent Tulare County at the Scripps National Spelling Bee beginning May 24 thanks to a special sponsoring partnership with the Visalia Times-Delta!

In partnership with Alianza Ecologista, Circle J-Norris Ranch is holding a two-day Community Biodiversity Festival this weekend - February 22-23. The public is invited to attend and participate in fun, hands-on activities suitable for the whole family. Beginning Saturday morning at 9:00 a.m., attendees can participate in the annual BioBlitz to document the biodiversity of Circle J utilizing the iNaturalist app. Following a lunch break, attendees will spend the afternoon planting trees for future wildlife habitats. On Sunday morning, the event will continue with guided nature walks, birding, and hiking.

A program of the SCICON school of outdoor education, Circle J-Norris Ranch is located at 41893 Yokohl Valley Road in Springville. Circle J offers all grade levels a wide variety of field study experiences.

For more information on the Community Biodiversity Festival, email Nancy Bruce at circlej@ocsnet.net.

Thank you Tulare County students for your impressive efforts at National History Day! Today, 200 elementary, middle and high school participants from 15 Tulare County schools entered 111 projects in the competition. Exploring the national theme, "Breaking Barriers in History," students created exhibits, performances, documentaries, historical papers, and websites to impress judges and audiences.

Special thanks to Jennifer Malone of the Wukchumni Tribe for a fascinating presentation on your work to preserve the tribe's language and art forms. Additional thanks to the Tulare County Historical Society for serving as judges and providing scholarships to support students advancing to the state competition in May! Check back at tcoe.org/historyday for a complete list of winners.

Don't miss Poetry Out Loud tomorrow night at 210 Café in downtown Visalia. Enjoy poetry recited by top high school students from Central Valley Christian, Tulare Union, and Mission Oak as they compete for the opportunity to represent Tulare County at the state finals in Sacramento, March 15-16.

The competition will begin at 6:00 p.m. Friday, February 7 at 210 Café (210 W. Center in downtown Visalia). Two-time county champion Gabrielle Trapse from Tulare Union High School will be returning.

Poetry Out Loud is a national competition. Participants select from an anthology of over 900 classic and contemporary poems, spanning a variety of cultures and genres.

The event is free and open to the public!

Educators - are you looking for a way to engage your students in the upcoming national census? To support census-based learning opportunities, TCOE is offering a training in state-developed curriculum for 5th, 8th, 11th, and 12th grades. The curriculum, entitled Count Me In!, can be used in both history-social science classrooms and with student leadership groups.

Educators are invited to attend free trainings of the Count Me In! curriculum at one of two available sessions on March 4 – 1:00 to 2:30 p.m. or 3:30 to 5:00 p.m. Educators who attend the training will receive access to all Count Me In! modules and materials, as well as a “how to” guide for student groups that want to create an awareness or “take action” census campaign.

To register for this free curriculum training, visit tulare.k12oms.org/147-182009.

Primary, secondary and post-secondary educators, industry partners, and representatives from workforce investment boards are invited to register for the third annual Tulare Kings College and Career Collaborative (TKCCC) Counselor Conference scheduled for January 28. The focus of this year’s event is data and its role in unlocking students’ success.

The conference will feature keynote speaker Terri Tchorzynski, who was the 2017 National School Counselor of the Year. Tomorrow evening, the Peña Planetarium will offer 6:00 and 7:00 pm showings of "Dawn of the Space Age." This immersive program chronicles man's first steps into space beginning with the launch of Sputnik and ending with private space exploration!

For program descriptions and more information on the public shows, visit http://www.tcoe.org/Planetarium/PublicShows.shtm.

The Peña Planetarium is located at 11535 Avenue 264 in Visalia, on the southwest corner of Mooney Boulevard and Avenue 264. Tickets are available at the Planetarium office only after 5:00 p.m. on the day of the shows. Tickets are $4 for adults and $3 for children 11 and under. Children must be accompanied by an adult. No late seating is offered once the planetarium doors close. For information, call (559) 737-6334.

The first annual TCOE Equity Conference is fast approaching with registration nearing capacity! Showcasing the latest research, the 2020 Equity Conference is designed to provide educators with information and resources to address the gaps in achievement for students from diverse backgrounds. The January 27 conference will feature two nationally-known speakers - Dr. Paul Gorski, founder and lead equity specialist for the Equity Literacy Institute, and Dr. Victor Rios, dean of Social Sciences and professor of Sociology at University of California, Santa Barbara. An additional 24 breakout sessions will be offered on topics that include district best practices, equity for EL students, social/emotional well-being, equity in student discipline, staff hiring practices, and chronic absenteeism.

Register today for just $15 for Tulare County educators and community members, or $25 for those outside the county! https://www.eventsquid.com/event.cfm?event_id=8119.

Hundreds of preschool children and their parents visited the annual Bright Start Parent/Infant Program holiday gathering. Little visitors were able to engage in a variety of fun, hands-on activities with the Bright Start staff who visit their homes to deliver support services. The children danced, made reindeer ornaments, created Christmas tree paintings featuring their tiny footprints, and even braved sometimes tearful pictures with Santa and Mrs. Claus!

Officers from the California Highway Patrol also attended the event to provide parents with proper car seat and booster seat use information. The Bright Start Program serves more than 1,000 children, ages 0-3, with home-based services, including physical, occupational, and speech therapies, behavior and feeding therapies, and parent training. For more information about Bright Start, visit tcoe.org/Special/BrightStart.

Tulare County Office of Education and County Superintendent of Schools Tim Hire wish you and your family Happy Holidays!

post_text:
Julie Westbrook, an education specialist who works at Strathmore Elementary, was named Educator of the Week as part of KSEE24’s valley-wide recognition program. Ms. Westbrook was surprised last week and presented with a $124 gift certificate from GW School Supply.

Ms. Westbrook has been working at Strathmore Elementary since joining TCOE’s Special Services Division in 2016. She works with students who have mild to moderate disabilities, either in class or one-on-one.

Ms. Westbrook’s story will be featured on KSEE24 News on December 18. She will also be honored at a reception for all 2019-2020 KSEE24 Educators of the Week on May 21 at Fresno State University. An engraved brick with her name will be installed on the Teachers and Friends of Education Honor Wall at Fresno State’s Kremen School of Education.

Congratulations Julie! Thank you KSEE24 for your work in recognizing Central Valley teachers.

Yesterday, the Tulare Kings College + Career Collaborative (TKCCC) hosted a Health Science & Medical Technology Industry Sector Summit for over 60 teachers and administrators representing eight high school districts, community college faculty, and workforce development professionals. TKCCC partners Kings County Job Training Office and Workforce Investment Board of Tulare County coordinated morning externship experiences with local business partners, including Adventist Health – Tulare, Adventist Health – Hanford, Family Healthcare Network, Kaweah Delta Healthcare District, and Sierra View Hospital. Through these externships, educators were given the opportunity to learn from local health care professionals about high demand jobs and skills students will need for a successful careers in the industry.

The groups then convened for an afternoon of collaboration, discussing local programs, available trainings, and labor market trends. Thank you partners for helping to provide an interactive and resourceful day for educators!
